      "date": "2012-11-07 14:16:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64, CentOS release 5.8/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/79e4f29e-28db-11e2-b672-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  1 tests failed: recovery-small.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "5c2e894d07154f44f6c5113cbd799c209ecd4fbe",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-07 17:18:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nOk, so it appears that unlike in a local setup, when we failover a remote MDS, it also somehow manages to reset fail_loc (modules unloaded/reloaded?)\n\nYuJian, what do you think would be the best way for me to retain fail_loc before mds restarts so that we actually hit that failure point?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "bdae52d56e715429def34c3f5e7b9c2988c0b0cd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-09 12:32:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n> Ok, so it appears that unlike in a local setup, when we failover a remote MDS, it also somehow manages to reset fail_loc (modules unloaded/reloaded?)\n\nPer facet_failover(), for SOFT failure mode, it mainly just does unmount and mount, without unloading and reloading modules. However, it will take more than 30 seconds to reach to the mount operation.\n\n> YuJian, what do you think would be the best way for me to retain fail_loc before mds restarts so that we actually hit that failure point?\n\nPer OBD_FAIL_TIMEOUT(OBD_FAIL_OSC_SHUTDOWN, 10), if OBD_FAIL_OSC_SHUTDOWN was hit, it will sleep 10 seconds. So, we have to make the \"lctl set_param fail_loc\" operation close to or right before the mount operation which is performed in mount_facet().\n\nThen we have to pass the fail_loc parameter along the path of facet_failover()->mount_facets()->mount_facet() and set the parameter inside the mount_facet() function right before the mount operation. Do I understand correctly?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "dc02bb54fc49c0ece9c43e4ff94039c03818741b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-10 10:25:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nthe thing is, I don't see the fail_loc hitting in the logs at all.\nSo I don't think 10 seconds wait is playing any role here.\nI definitely see fail_loc hitting when doing a single node test locally, though.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "db382e35357bc3c412bc263918ec267061dbc19a",
